 orthopedics and dermatology, where visualizing the exact nature and extent of a condition is crucial. Doctors can use these holographic images to plan treatment strategies and present more effective solutions to patients, ensuring better understanding and communication of complex medical concepts.</p><p>Additionally, clinics use holographic displays in patient education, where doctors can show patients detailed 3D representations of their conditions. This empowers patients to understand their health better and make informed decisions about treatment options. Furthermore, these displays can be used for follow-up care, where healthcare providers visualize the effects of prescribed treatments on patients' health over time. The integration of holographic displays in clinics is expected to increase patient engagement, improve medical outcomes, and reduce miscommunication during consultations.</p><h2>Others</h2><p>The "Others" segment includes various sectors where medical holographic displays are being implemented beyond traditional hospital and clinic environments. These include research institutions, medical schools, and healthcare product development companies. In research settings, holographic displays assist in creating detailed models for studying diseases, enabling researchers to simulate and analyze how different factors impact biological systems. This is critical in drug development and medical device innovation, where precision and a deep understanding of biological structures can lead to groundbreaking advancements in treatments.</p><p>In medical education, holographic displays provide a dynamic tool for teaching students about human anatomy and complex medical processes. Rather than relying solely on traditional textbooks or static 2D images, medical schools can use 3D holograms to give students an interactive, realistic understanding of the human body. This method has proven to enhance the learning experience and improve retention rates among medical studen